<TITLE> Security key for growth: Mirza Aziz </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, Nov 16 (bdnews24.com)  Finance adviser AB Mirza Azizul Islam has said the economy will continue to grow if political unrest does not upset public security. "If law and order is maintained then export earnings and the flow of remittance from the expatriate communities will come in unhindered," Azizul said to reporters after a meeting with a team from the World Bank. He also said all uncertainties about the elections would soon disappear. "The government believes that an election with the participation of all parties will be held on Dec. 18." He, however, would not predict any situation in case the election did not take place. The adviser pointed to the link between law and order and the development of industries, job generation and social progress. Azizul also whoever took office, they should attach top priority to agriculture. "The World Bank has pledged $134 crore to Bangladesh in loan and already a deal involving $80 crore has been finalised." He added that by next June the remaining funds would be made available. The adviser, however, warned that if the global economic crisis persisted, the flow of foreign aid to may drop in the 2010-11 fiscal year. To prepare for any contingencies, he said, the ministries should finalise their 'portfolios' regarding their demand of foreign aid. "The government will finalise a portfolio after getting proposals from all ministries," he said. World Bank official John Romy termed the economic management of Bangladesh "satisfactory". "The global economic turmoil has not affected Bangladesh and the main challenges of the elected government will be to alleviate poverty and ensure economic development," he said after the meeting. bdnews24
